$ Windows code pages

? A *code page* maps the numbers 0 through 255 to a character.

There are two groups of → Windows code pages:
  • OEM: used by *console applications* (→ Windows/console-host[console host]?)
  • ANSI (which is a misnomer and is officially called *Windows code pages*)

The code page for → development/Unicode/UTF-8 is 65001.

sa:
  → Windows/development/code-page/byte-2-char[byte-2-char.c] is a simple C program that converts the bytes between 128 and 255 to selected code pages and the
  write an → development/web/HTML/tags/table[html table].

  In → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/cmd_exe[cmd.exe], the code page can be displayed or changed with → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/chcp_com[`chcp`] and
  → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/cmd_exe/commands/mode[`mode con: cp`].

  The `C_codepage.NLS` files under → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32

  The original IBM PC's codepage was → Windows/development/code-page/437[437].

  → Windows/registry[Registry] key → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT/MIME/Database/Codepage[`HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT\MIME\Database\Codepage`]

  → development/Unicode/character-encoding
